-! # how to errors: 042-main-invalid-return.zo
-!
-! @cmd: `zo build 042-main-invalid-return.zo`
-!
-! The `main` function is the "Front Door" of your workstation. 
-! When it finishes, it returns control to the Operating System.
-!
-! The OS is simple: it only understands a status number (like `0` for 
-! success). If you try to return a `str` or a `tuple`, the OS will 
-! be "Working Blind." zo prevents this mismatch at the very start.

-- Mistake: `main` cannot return a string.
fun main() -> str {
  "done"
}

-! ## try this.
-!
-!   1. Change the return type to `int` and return `0`.
-!   2. Remove the `-> str` entirely. In zo, functions return `void` (nothing)
-!      by default.
-!   3. The entry point is a contract with the hardware. We keep that contract
-!      strict to ensure your program exits cleanly.

-- EXPECTED OUTPUT:
-- [E0582] Error: Invalid return type
--     ╭─[ 042-main-invalid-return.zo:13:15 ]
--     │
--  13 │ fun main() -> str {
--     │               ─┬─
--     │                ╰─── invalid return type
--     │
--     │ Help: Remove the return type or use `fun main() {}`
--     │
--     │ Note: The `main` function is the program entry point.
--     │       It must return unit (no value)
-- ────╯
-- [E0575] Error: Type mismatch
--     ╭─[ 042-main-invalid-return.zo:13:1 ]
--     │
--  13 │ fun main() -> str {
--     │ ─┬─
--     │  ╰─── incompatible types for this operation
--     │
--     │ Note: The types of both operands must be compatible
-- ────╯
